No re-entry.","ageLimitCode":"OVER_18","ageLimit":"18 and Over","showTypeCode":null,"showType":"","eventStatusCode":"BUY","eventStatus":"Buy","eventStatusMessage":"","ticketPurchaseUrl":"https://www.ticketfly.com/purchase/event/1317667?utm_medium=api","ticketPrice":"$10.00","externalTicketingUrls":[],"multiEventCartable":true,"facebookEventId":531884243673778,"facebookEventIdString":"531884243673778","headliners":[{"id":1213547,"name":"Raging Fire","startTime":null,"eventDescription":"As charter members of Nashville’s original 1980s underground scene, Raging Fire merged DIY punk with feminism and southern culture to forge an innovative sound that foreshadowed the modern rock of the 1990s. Their 1985 EP A Family Thing is considered a landmark in Nashville rock and the band made increasingly sophisticated music through the end of the decade. In 2015, Raging Fire released an anthology on CD and vinyl of re-mastered record tracks, compilation cuts, and unreleased demos entitled Everything is Roses: 1985 – 1989. The record was nationally acclaimed and the reformed band made a triumphant return to live performance at a venue they knew well: Nashville’s venerable Exit/In. Since that time Raging Fire has continued to play together and recently recorded tracks for new record scheduled for a prerelease debut at their Exit/In show on November 26th. This record, entitled These Teeth are Sharp, will feature new recordings of unreleased songs both old and new. TRUE STORY: Barely of legal drinking age, Michael Godsey, Mark Medley, and Les Shields were experienced veterans of the Nashville punk/hardcore scene when they met Vanderbilt student Melora Zaner in late 1983. Originally dubbed “Ring of Fire,” the band’s initial look and sound was inspired by punk Americana such as Jason and the Scorchers, the Gun Club, and X. After playing their third show opening for The Cramps at Chicago’s Cabaret-Metro in May 1984 they spent the summer touring the south and mid-west, and in September became Raging Fire. * Encouraged by a strong Nashville following and the “anything is possible” DIY spirit of the times, the band began recording tracks in late 1984 with their friend Mike Poole, and the subsequent EP entitled A Family Thing was released in April 1985 on their own Pristine Records. As the record was enthusiastically received by the burgeoning college radio industry, Raging Fire returned to the road in 1985, playing everywhere from Chicago to New Orleans, Detroit, and Athens, Georgia. * Unfortunately for the band, resources were limited and the first pressing of the EP ran out just as nationwide airplay was reaching its peak. A second pressing was eventually completed but effective record distribution proved unwieldy. Over the course of the next three and half years the band would continue to make music and tour from Austin to Manhattan in their quest for a nationwide audience. In 1986 they released the LP Faith Love Was Made Of, as well as appeared on the Vanderbilt WRVU radio compilation City Without a Subway, the Nashville Entertainment Association’s 1988 Hear Rock City, and the 1989 compilation Ten of Kind, a joint production of College Music Journal (CMJ) and BMG Records. * In addition, Raging Fire was first on CMJ’s short list of top unsigned bands in 1987 (along with the Pixies) and that same year made the first of several CMJ Music Marathon and New Music Seminar appearances. Meanwhile, their music continued to evolve as they performed increasingly powerful and sophisticated songs for large audiences in Nashville at all age shows, nightclubs, and public music festivals. But despite good fortune and great effort, national exposure evaded Raging Fire. By late 1989 major record labels remained puzzled by the band’s unique sound as well as the fact they were from Nashville –a place known at the time only for country music and southern rock. By early 1990 the members of the band all moved on to other projects. * In existence for little more than six years, Raging Fire left a legacy of passionate live shows and compelling original recordings. Their music from 1984 through 1989 documents the transformation of a melodic punk band to a modern rock prototype. With the mainstream breakout of modern rock in the 1990s, Raging Fire’s music was finally proven visionary. In 2015 the band celebrated the 30 years since the first record with the acclaimed anthology Everything is Roses: 1984 -1989.
